{"/service/ndnp/arhi/batch_arhi_jupiter_ver01/data/sn90050267/00513688763/1908011301/0234.xml":{"full_text":"VOL. 3\nDAVIS DIDN\u2019T SPEAK.\nFAILED TO SHOW UP AT JACKSON DAY\nBANQUET\nThe metropolitan press is again\nbeen devoting considerable spac^ to\nour own Senator Jeff Davis.\nThe senator was down on the pro\ngram for an address before the De\nmocracy of Chicago at the Jackson\nday banquet, but failed to put in an\nappearance, although he arrived in\nthe city several hours before the time\nfor the blow-out. The senator de\nclares he was too ill to attend the\ngathering, his private secretary says\nthe senator, worn out from a long\njourney, fell asleep in his room and\ndid not awake until the banquet was\nalmost over, and some newspaper cor\nrespondents are so uncharitable as to\ninsinuate that the cause of the sen\nator's absence was that he imbibed too\nfreely of seltzer water or some other j\nbeverage, or perhaps both, and that;\nwhen the hour arrived for him to de-1\nliver his speech his tongue had be-I\ncame so swollen and his throat so dry i\nthat he could not articulate, and for\nthis reason his friends induced him 1\nto remain in his room and undergo\nthe usual treatment for such ailments.\nTn regard to Senator Davis\u2019 contin\nued and long absence from his duties\nat Washington, a recent dispatch\nsays:\n\u201cSurprise is giving way to anxiety\non the part of many of the democratic\nsenators over the continued absence\nof Senator \u201cJeff\u201d Davis of Arkan\nsas, from bis duties in the senate.\nSenator Davis disappeared from\nWashington the dav after he made his\nmaiden speech early in December and\nhas not been in his seat since. He has\nmissed two opportunities of advanc\ning his position on committees and\nmissed a chance to shift himself to a\nmore advantageous position.\nSenator William James Bryan of\nFlorida, the younger member, ob\ntained the seat which would have\ngone to Davis.\nOwing to the declaration in his first\nspeech that the trust had boasted that\nthey would soon \u201chave him eating out\nof their bands.\u201d and his protest that\nthis would never happen, several of\nthe minority members today declared\nthat he had undoubtedly gone into\nhiding to avoid capture.\nBy remaining absent for the first\nfour weeks of his first session Sen\nator Davis has broken all records,\nsince new senators seldom miss the\nThe Maxfield National Bank\nHAS resumed making liberal Cash\nAdvances on Stored cotton. _____\nEverybody is invited to j oin this Bank in\nits liberal, progressive and \u201cLive and\nLet Live Methods.\u2019\u2019\nIt will continue to pay interest on Savings\nDeposits.\nAbsolute Security is Guaranteed its Patrons\nDIRECTORS:\nTHEO. MAXFIELD PAXTON THOMAS\nF. D. FULKERSON ALLEN A. MAXFIELD\nA. J. CRAIG CHAS. F. COLE\nE. L. GIVENS T. SIDNEY MAXFIELD.\nTHE DAILY GUARD.\nopening prayer and the closing exec\nutive meeting of a single session dur\ning the first fotfr or five months con\ngress is in session.\nWANTED TO GO TO JAIL.\nAGED DERELICT COMMITTED MISDEMEAN\nOR FOR THIS PURPOSE.\nHot Springs, Jan. 11.\u2014Frank Mc-\nCoy, a vagrant, fully 70 years of age,\nwho had been denied the shelter of\nthe city jail, broke into prison this\nmorning in a new and novel manner.\nJust two days ago he had been given\nenough money to purchase a ticket for\nLittle Rock, but he had evidently\nbeen sent back again, for he appeared\nlast night and asked for lodging at\nthe jail. This morning he was found\nin the waiting room at the Rock Is\nland depot and when put out, picked\nup a big club and drove it through\nthe window. He admitted that he com\nmitted the act for the purpose of\nbreaking into jail and there is no\nI doubt but that he will be successful,\n'for a charge of vagrancy and malic\nious destruction of property has been\nI lodged against him.\nORDER TRAINS RESTORED.\nOn complaint of patrons along the\nKnobel Helena Branch of the Iron\nMountain, the State Railroad Com\nmission has ordered a restoration of\ndouble passenger service on that\nbranch, to take effect by Feb. Ist. At\npresent there is only one passenger\ntrain each way per day, double ser\nvice having been discontinued Dec.\n10th last.\nThe Commission has also ordered\nthe erection of a depot with proper\nfacilities for handling freight and the\naccommodation of passengers at Mc-\nGehee.\nLUMBER MILLS RESUME.\nINDUSTRIAL CONDITIONS ALL OVER THE\nCOUNTRY IMPROVING.\nThat the industrial depression is\nabout over is shown by the resump\ntion of many factories and mills\nthroughout the country. In Missis\nsippi a alrge number of lumber mills,\nwhich closed down some time ago\nhave resumed.\nAt Bimingham many iron fur\nnaces have started up, and many fac\ntories in Georgia have resumed and\nsimilar reports come from all over\nthe south.\nBATESVILLE, ARK., MONDAY EV ENING, JANUARY 13, 1908.\nTHE INSANE ASYLUM.\nDR. STINSON GIVES SOME INTERESTING\nFACTS AROUT THAT INSTITUTION.\nThe following information relating\nto the state insane asylum and insane\npersons is given out by Dr. Stinson,\nhead physician of that institution..\nPractically all alienists differ in\ntheir opinions regarding the treatment\nof diseases of the mind.\nThirty per cent of the patients\ntaken into the Arkansas hospital are\ndischarged as cured each year.\nThe targe majority of insanity\ncases is attributable to heredity.\nPractically no negro insane patients\nare are cured.\nThe female negro patients are par\nticularly subject to tuberculosis.\nA standing rule, which is rigidly\nenforced in the Arkansas hospital, is\nthat any employe or attendant who\nuses harsh measures with patients is\ndischarged without question.\nMany cases of insanity are caused\nby worry over financial or family mat\nters, and complete rest and quiet, with\nall necessaries provided, often restore\nsuch cases to their normal condition.\nCases of insanity caused by illness,\nor a shock, are more difficult to treat,\nand many times never yield.\nThe presence of pool and billiard\ntables in the wards where no violent\npatients are confined, and cards in the\nothers, has proven a great aid in keep\ni ing the minds of the inmates occupied.\nThere are in round numbers some\n100 insane inhabitants of Arkansas\nnot in the hospital. There is no room\nfor them.\nKindness is the ruling idea at the\nhospital. Actual restraint is never re\nsorted to until all other means have\nproven unavailing.\nWherever it is possible, the inmates\nare allowed to perform such work in\nand around the hospital as is condu\ncive to their well-being.\nThe science of medicine is very in\naccurate, and practitioners are con\ntinually learning much which will be\nof material benefit to coming genera\ntions.\nA GOOD SHOWING.\nDUNN\u2019S REPORT SHOWS PANIC LIGHTLY\nFELT IN ARKANSAS.\nDespite the financial panic which\nbefell the country in the latter months\nof last year, Arkansas survived the\ndepression with less business failures\nlt\u201c-\u00bbn occurred in the year 1906, a rec\noTc^^iaF is specifically mentioned in\na compilation given in the annual re\nport of Dun\u2019s Review The commer\ncial agency, after detailing the in\ncreased number of failures in many\nother states in the south, far west and\nsouthwest, says that failures were\nfewer in Arkansas and the defaulted\nindebtedness was smaller. In 1906\nthere were 306 failures, with liabil\nities of $1,648,966, while in 1907 there\nwere 291 failures, a reduction of 15.\nThe liabilities for the 1907 failures\namounted to $1,259,032, or $389,934\nless than those of the preceding year.\nArkansas' excellent showing is con\nsidered as another indication of the\nsplendid condition of both banks and\nbusiness houses in the sttae.\nA CONSIDERATE FATHER.\nNot long since, in an Arkansas\ntown, the father of a young man who\nhad chosen the profession of law, but\nwho possessed a mania for drinking,\nand gambling, told his son that he\nwould buy him a good law library if\nhe (the son) didn\u2019t think it would\nconflict with his drinking and gamb\nling.\nFEDERAL INCOME SHRINKS.\nBARTHOLD SAYS HEAVY DEFICIT CON\nFRONTS THE GOVERNMENT.\nWashington, Jan. 12.\u2014\u201c The Six\ntieth congress has been in actual ses\nsion only a few days and more than\n600 bills alrealy have been intro\nduced for the expenditure of about\n$80,000,000 in proposed public build\nings. If 20 per cent of that total is\nappropriated during the present ses\nsion the people of the country may\nconsider themselves lucky.\u201d\nThe foregoing statement was made\nby Chairman Barthold of the house\ncommittee on public buildings and\ngrounds.\n\u201cGovernment revenues,\u201d he said,\n\u201care falling short at the rate of one\nmillion dollars a month, due to the\ncurtailment of the luxury purchases\nby the people in this time of financial\ndisturbance and commercial depres\nsion. We face a heavy deficit at the\nclose of the fiscal year.\u201d\nPOLITICIANS IN MEMPHIS.\nTO TAKE PART IN ST. FRANCIS LI .EE\nBOARD CONFERENCE.\nMemphis, Tenn., Jan. 11. \u2014John W.\nCrockett, railroad commissioner, Sec\nretay of State O. C. Ludwig ind\nAgricultural Commissioner G. B.\nTucker, arrived in the city tonight.\nGovernor Pindall is expected tomor\nrow, when a conference will be held\nwith W. B. Miller, president of the\nSt. Francis Levee Board; James Bush\ntreasurer, and H. F. Roleson, attor\nney. All parties refused to be inter\nviewed, but other levee board officials\nhere say that the conference will be\nheld for the purpose of bringing the\nLevee Board in line to fight Kirby for\nGovernor.\nKILLING AT CLARENDON.\nIn a difficulty at Clarendon Ladd\nCarruth, aged 30 years, was instantly\nkilled by Dolph Bowers.\nHe and shrdlu mfwyp mfwyppp\nCarruth and Bowers engaged in a\nfistic encounter on a porch, and Bow\ners knocked Carruth from the porch\nto a concrete sidewalk. Carruth fall\ning on his head and neck. His neck\nwas broken, and death followed im\nmediately. Bowers was arrested and\nplaced in jail. It is alleged that Car\nruth had been drinking, and that he\nfirst had trouble with a man by the\nname of Flinn in Lofton\u2019s restaurant.\nThe two are said to have engaged in\na fight with knives, each escaping ser\nious injury. Carruth then left the\nrestaurant and later became embroil\ned in a quarrel with Bowers, who,\nit is claimed, took up Flinn\u2019s side of\nthe former quarrel.\n\u201cNO PROPERTY FOUND.\u201d\nA young man from Liberty town\nship came down a few days ago and\napplied to County Clerk Sims for the\nnecessary papers authorizing him to\nwed one of that township\u2019s fairest\ndaughters. Being of lawful age and\nhaving the required surety along with\nhim, the clerk at once pvt his fist to\nthe desired document,\nA few days later the license was re\nturned, endorsed \u201cNo Property found\u201d\nIt is not definitely known as to wheth\ner or not the sarch will be renewed.\nDividend Number 37\nTHE BANK Os BATESVILLE\nHas just declared its Thirty-Seventh Semi-\nAnnual Diviaend, being 10 per cent out of\nits earnings for the last six months, say\n$5,000, and had several hundred dollars left\nover as undivided profits.\nWith our Loans somewhat less than they\nwere a year ago; our Expenses decidedly\nless and our Deposits a good many thous\nand dollars more than they were a year\nago, we enter on the New Year with bright\ner prospects than ever, in spite of the fact\nthat we have just emerged from the worst\nfinancial panic we have ever experienced.\nWe sincerely thank our friends and custom\ners for their loyalty. May the New Year\nbring you, one and all, good health and\nprosperity. We solicit your future busi\nness and will serve you the best we can.\nBank of Batesville\nCapital and Surplus SIOO,OOO\nNO. 98.\nDIDN\u2019T KNOW IT WAS LOADED.\nCROWD AT HOG KILLING FRIGHTENED BY\nCIVIL WAR RELIC.\nAfter having been regarded as\nharmless and used as a \u201cplaything\u201d\nby the children of that community for\nIthe last forty-five years, an old can\nnon ball exploded in the yard of Hen\nry Spence at Middlebrook last Tues\nday morning, which came very near\nresulting in the death of some half a\njdozen men, women and children who\nwere assisting at hog killing. The old\nbomb-shell or cannon ball was a relic\nof the civil war and had been in the\npossession of the Spence family since\nit was found, near a soldier\u2019s camp at\nPittman\u2019s ferry at the outbreak of the\ncivil war. On Tuesday Mr. Spence,\nwith the help of some of his neighbors\nwas killing hogs. They built a fire un\nder a couple of wash kettles prepara\ntory to scalding the hogs when all of\na sudden there was a flash, a jar, a\nloud report, and both kettles were\nblown into atoms. Mr. Spence was\nknocked senseless by the shock, but\nnobody else was hurt. By some over\nsight or carelessness the fire was built\non the old bomb-shell, which weighed\nsome ten or fifteen pounds, and of\ncourse nobody knew it was loaded.\u2014\nPocahontas Star-Herald.\nBANISHES CIGARETTES.\nISLAND OF ST. HELENA FORBIDS BOYS TO\nSMOKE THEM.\nSt. Henelna is determined to sup\npress juvenile smoking. The new\nlaw that has just come into force in\nthe lonely little Napoleonic island of\nSt. Helena would probably be deemed\nDraconian by the average youngster.\nAny person giving or selling tobacco\nto boys or girls under the age of 16\nlis liable to a fine of 20 shillings for\nthe first offense. Boys detected in the\n\u25a0act of smoking or in the possession of\nof tobacco or cigarettes are liable to\na fine of 5 shillings and 12 strokes\nwith the birch.\nMr. and Mrs. W. K. Estes came up\nlast Friday to pay their son, Jasper\nEstes, a farewell visit before leaving\nfor Trent, Texas, which place they\nwill make their future home. Other\nmembers of Mr. Estes\u2019 family joined\nthem at Guion Saturday and on Mon\nday they departed for their western\nhome, followed by the best wishes of\na host of friends. Mr. Estes was\nclerk of Izard county for a number of\nyears and no county in the state ever\nhad a better or more accommodating\nofficial.\u2014Calico Rock Progress.","height":"18411","width":"11967"}}
